Primary medical amenities such as CHPS compounds and clinics are the initial stop during illness; they provide essential health care services. Table 2
                         indicates that 29.95%, 61.49%, and 93.67% of people in the Upper West Region could walk to the nearest primary health facility within 2 km, 5 km, and 20 km, respectively. This implies that less than half (29.95%) of the population of Upper West Region has high access to primary health facilities, while 61.49% have access within the 5 km distance to health facilities as recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO). About 312,311 residents, representing 38.51% of the total population within the region, are outside the 5 km radius, the recommended optimum distance to a health facility. At the district level, the mean, minimum, and maximum percentage of people within a 2 km walking distance of the nearest primary health facility were 26.44%, 11.29%, and 81.75%, respectively. Wa Municipal has the highest number of inhabitants within a 2 km walk of the nearest primary health facility (81.75%), while Sissala East recorded the least (11.29%) (Table 2 and Fig. 4
                        ). The mean, minimum, and maximum percentages of people within a 5-km radius of the nearest primary health facility were 61.24%, 26.46%, and 94.42%, respectively. Sissala East recorded the lowest percent of inhabitants (26.46%) within a 5 km radius from the nearest primary health facility. Wa East and Sissala East had the highest percentage of their inhabitants, i.e., 67% and 74%, respectively, beyond the recommended 5 km travel distance to the nearest primary health facility. These populations are underserved and are compelled to travel longer distances to access basic health care in times of sickness, which may be inconvenient for the elderly, expectant mothers, and the disabled. On the other hand, the entire population of three districts, i.e., Wa Municipal, Lawra Municipal, and Nandom Distict, are relatively well served and can access the nearest primary health facility within 5 km.

Fig. 7
 shows spatial access to district hospitals in the Upper West Region. It demonstrates how roads facilitate or limit healthcare accessibility in the region. Per Ghana's Planning Standards, a district hospital is intended to service the whole district. This suggests that inhabitants anywhere within the district should be able to reach a district hospital within a reasonable travel time preferable 30 min drive (Bosanac, Parkinson, & Hall, 1976). Per the 30 min threshold, 387,597 inhabitants representing 48% of the total population of the region can reach the nearest district hospital within 30 min drive. Out of this number, 9.77% lies within the first quartile (25th percentile), 48% within the middle quartile (50th percentile) and then 85% within the upper quartile (75th percentile) (Fig. 8
). Within an hour's drive, 78% of the population is served while 95% can access the nearest district hospital within 2 h drive.
